Pestalotiopsis

-like species are pathogens which can cause numerous diseases in different hosts and are widely distributed in tropical and temperate ecosystems (

; 

; 

). Tea gray blight is one of the most serious leaf diseases of tea trees, caused by the phytopathogenic fungus 

Pseudopestalotiopsis theae
(Sawada) Maharachch. K.D. Hyde & Crous (Sporocadaceae)

, affecting the production and quality of tea worldwide (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). However, the pathogenic substances in 

P. theae

that cause tea gray blight have not been identified. Knowledge of these pathogenic substances can facilitate the development of disease control strategies, such as gene modification to improve host resistance and the identification of toxin biosynthesis inhibitors or toxin deactivators (

; 

). Therefore, the study of pathogenic substances is indispensable for fully understanding the pathogenic mechanism.

Weeds have long been considered one of the most dangerous biotic stresses for crop production (

). Although synthetic herbicides have always been used as an effective strategy for weed control and indeed play a huge role in the development of agriculture, excessive and inappropriate use has resulted in the evolution of resistant weeds, environmental pollution, food contamination, and more is a serious threat to human and animal health (

). Consequently, the development of new herbicides with high-efficiency and low-toxicity based on the usage of fungal phytotoxins as natural bioherbicides are of great significance for crop protection. At present, fungal phytotoxins are generally regarded as one of the important resources for the development of eco-friendly and safe bioherbicides (

; 

; 

).

Compound 1 was obtained as a yellowish oil. The molecular formula of 1 was determined to be C 16 H 22 O 4 by HR-ESI-MS analysis, which requires six degrees of unsaturation. The 1 H, 13 C, DEPT, and HSQC NMR spectra revealed that 1 contains 16 carbons, including three methyls [ δ H 1.90 (H 3 -11), 1.68 (H 3 -15) and 1.75 (H 3 -16); δ C 23.6 (C-11), 18.2 (C-15) and 26.3(C-16)], two methylenes [ δ H 5.25 (H-10, olefinic) and 2.50 (H-12); δ C 121.9 (C-10, olefinic) and 34.2 (C-12)], five methines [ δ H 4.01(H-1, oxygenated), 4.42 (H-3, oxygenated), 3.84 (H-4, oxygenated), 5.89 (H-5, olefinic) and 5.34 (H-13, olefinic); δ C 71.2 (C-1, oxygenated), 72.9 (C-3, oxygenated), 67.9 (C-4, oxygenated), 136.9 (C-5, olefinic) and 119.9 (C-13, olefinic)], and six quaternary carbons [ δ C 77.1 (C-2, oxygenated), 125.4 (C-6, olefinic), 88.6 (C-7, alkyne carbon), 91.2 (C-8, alkyne carbon), 128.5 (C-9, olefinic) and 135.5 (C-14, olefinic)]. These data of 1 ( Table 1 ) were similar to those of biscognienyne B (7) (
;
), except that the oxygenated carbons at δ C 77.1 (C-2) and δ C 72.9 (C-3) were significantly shifted to the downfield region in the spectrum of 1 compared to those of 7. This result implied there were two hydroxyl groups at C-2 ( δ C 77.1) and C-3 ( δ C 72.9) in 1 instead of the epoxy unit in 7, which was supported by HR-ESI-MS analysis. The planar structure of 1 was further confirmed by 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC correlation analyses ( Fig. 2 ). The stereochemistry of 1 was suggested to be the same as that of 7, for which the absolute configuration was determined by comparison of the coupling constants, NOE correlations ( Fig. 3 ), specific optical rotation value, and biogenesis. The absolute configuration of 1 was further supported by a combination of electronic circular dichroism (ECD) calculations based on time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT) method at the B3LYP/6-31G (d, p) level with the ECD spectra experimentally collected in methanol ( Fig. 4 ). 1 was named biscognienyne G.

The remaining two known compounds from 

P. theae

were identified based on their spectroscopic data and the literature. These natural products were identified as biscognienyne D (6) (

), biscognienyne B (7) (

).

Inspired by the fact that phytotoxins produced by pathogenic fungus are an effective resource for designing natural and safe bioherbicides (

; 

; 

), sufficient amounts of compounds 1–4 and 8 were selected and assayed the herbicidal activity through Petri dish bioassays (

). Due to insufficient amounts of compounds 5–7, their herbicidal activities were not evaluated. Compounds 1–4 showed phytotoxic effects inhibiting seed germination and seedling growth of 

S. viridis

(
Figs. 5–8
). The germination percentage values of seeds treated with compounds 1–4 ranged from 5% to 16%, while that of seeds in the control reached 62% (
Figs. 5–8
). Compound 8 (germination percentage value 55%) did not significantly inhibit the seed germination of 

S. viridis

, with respect to the control (
Figs. 5–8
). Furthermore, radicle and germ length were strongly inhibited by compounds 1–4, while little phytotoxic effects toward seedling growth of 

S. viridis

were observed in the case of compound 8 (
Figs. 5–8
). The alkyne group could be the key factor for the phytotoxicity of this 
type
of meroterpenoids.

Conformational searches of the relative energy within 5.0 kcal/mol were performed using molecular mechanics force-field (MMFF94s) calculations with CONFLEX software (

). ECD calculations were performed on the conformers using time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT) at the B3LYP/6-31G (d,p) level in methanol with the polarizable continuum model (PCM) (

). The simulated spectra of the conformers were averaged based on the Boltzmann distribution theory and the relative Gibbs free energy of the conformers to obtain the final spectra (

).
